{{islamophobia}}
==Incidents country wise==
===Bosnia===
[[Image:Srebrenica Massacre - Exhumed Grave of Victims - Potocari 2007.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Mass grave where events of the [[Srebrenica massacre]] of [[Bosniaks|Bosnian]] Muslims unfolded]]
[[File:Srebrenica2007.jpg|thumb|Burial of 465 identified [[Bosniak]]s in 2007.]]
{{Main|Bosnian Genocide}}
{{See|Fo<U+010D>a massacres|Srebrenica massacre|Omarska camp}}

In the 1990s, the [[Bosnian Genocide]] and [[Kosovo War]], both of which involved the "mass murder of innocent Muslims," have been linked to Islamophobia.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Z. Husain & D. M. Rosenbaum|contribution=Perceiving Islam: The Causes and Consequences of Islamophobia in the Western Media|title=Religious fundamentalism in the contemporary world: critical social and political issues|editor=Santosh C. Saha|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|year=2004|isbn=0-7391-0760-7|pages=177<U+2013>8|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> In Bosnia, Christian [[Serb]] and [[Croat]] militias carried out genocidal attacks on the Muslim [[Bosniak]] community. According to the [[International Committee of the Red Cross|ICRC]] data on the Bosnian Genocide, "200,000 people were killed, 12,000 of them children, up to 50,000 women were raped, and 2.2 million were forced to flee their homes."<ref>[http://www.un.org/ga/63/generaldebate/pdf/bosniaherzegovina_en.pdf Statement by Dr. Haris Silajd<U+017E>i<U+0107> Chairman of the Presidency Bosnia and Herzegovina, Head of the Delegation of Bosnia and Herzegovina. at the 63rd Session of the General Assembly on the occasion of the General Debate], [http://www.un.org/ga/63/generaldebate/bosniaandherzegovina.shtml Summary], 23 September 2008, pp. 2.</ref>  Many attacks on religious buildings and symbols took place in towns such as [[Fo<U+010D>a]], where all of the town's [[mosque]]s were destroyed. On 22 April 1992, Serbs blew up the Alad<U+017E>a Mosque and eight more mosques dating from the 16th and 17th centuries were damaged or completely destroyed. On January 1994, the Serb authorities renamed Fo<U+010D>a <U+201C>Srbinje<U+201D> ({{lang-sr|<U+0421><U+0440><U+0431><U+0438><U+045A><U+0435>}}), literally meaning "place of the Serbs" (from ''Srbi'' Serbs and ''-nje'' which is a Slavic locative suffix).<ref name="ICTY: Kunarac, Kova<U+010D> and Vukovi<U+0107> judgement - Fo<U+010D>a">{{cite web|url=http://www.un.org/icty/kunarac/trialc2/judgement/kun-tj010222e-5.htm#VC|title=ICTY: The attack against the civilian population and related requirements}}{{Dead link|date=December 2009}}</ref>

===Bulgaria===
In 1989, 310,000 Turks left Bulgaria, many under pressure as a result of the [[communist]] [[Todor Zhivkov|Zhivkov]] regime's assimilation campaign (though up to a third returned before the end of the year). That program, which began in 1984, forced all Turks and other Muslims in Bulgaria to adopt [[Bulgarian name]]s and renounce all Muslim customs. The motivation of the 1984 assimilation campaign is unclear; however, some experts believe that the disproportion between the birth rates of the Turks and the Bulgarians was a major factor.<ref name=autogenerated1>Glenn E. Curtis, ed. Bulgaria: A Country Study. Washington: GPO for the Library of Congress, 1992</ref> During the name-changing phase of the campaign, Turkish towns and villages were surrounded by army units. Citizens were issued new identity cards with Bulgarian names. Failure to present a new card meant forfeiture of salary, pension payments, and bank withdrawals. Birth or marriage certificates would be issued only in Bulgarian names. Traditional Turkish costumes were banned; homes were searched and all signs of Turkish identity removed. [[Mosques]] were closed. According to estimates, 500 to 1,500 people were killed when they resisted assimilation measures, and thousands of others were imprisoned or sent to labor camps or were forcibly resettled.<ref>Library of Congress, [http://memory.loc.gov/frd/cs/bgtoc.html A Country Study: Bulgaria], Call Number DR55.B724 1993</ref>

===Canada===
Halima Mautbur, from the [[Canadian Council on American-Islamic Relations]] called an attack on a [[hijab]]i Muslim woman "an Islamophobic incident".<ref>[http://www.news.utoronto.ca/inthenews/archive/2006_03_16.html Muslim groups want action from U of T]{{dead link|date=October 2010}}, ''University of Toronto News'', March 16, 2006</ref> Hamilton police<U+2019>s [[hate crime]] unit and chief [[arson]] investigator discovered "evidence of [[vandalism]] at the property as well as an incendiary device".<ref>
